<span id="freeTextContainer6077361210301696061">THIS IS NOT MY PERSONAL OPINION<br/><br/>IT IS THAT OF MY CLOSE FRIEND JOE<br/><br/>I suspect someone more familiar with the players and their theories would get even more out of this, but I definitely feel more kindly and receptive toward these eggheads, having seen through this their human sides and their passionate struggles to reach truth. Their integrity requires ruefully accepting it time and again when the newest genius tears down the fortress of truth each thought he had built. The constant questioning of p</span>
  <span id="freeText6077361210301696061" style="display:none">THIS IS NOT MY PERSONAL OPINION<br /><br />IT IS THAT OF MY CLOSE FRIEND JOE<br /><br />I suspect someone more familiar with the players and their theories would get even more out of this, but I definitely feel more kindly and receptive toward these eggheads, having seen through this their human sides and their passionate struggles to reach truth. Their integrity requires ruefully accepting it time and again when the newest genius tears down the fortress of truth each thought he had built. The constant questioning of principles and fervent desire to locate truth has been associated with "madness', and that comes up in this, too. The drawing is engaging and witty. The story concludes, satisfyingly in an unexpected way, with a performance of the Orestia. Kudos to the author for coming up with such a well-executed and thought-expanding book.</span>
